think like from last chapter - strong signal of overall linear growth makes hard to see subtler trends - model captures steady growth over time, and residuals will show whats left
r # know how to do this for one country nz <- filter(gapminder, country == "New Zealand") nz %>% ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp)) + geom_line() + ggtitle("Full data = ")
r nz_mod <- lm(lifeExp ~ year, data = nz) nz %>% add_predictions(nz_mod) %>% ggplot(aes(year, pred)) + geom_line() + ggtitle("Linear trend + ")
r nz %>% add_residuals(nz_mod) %>% ggplot(aes(year, resid)) + geom_hline(yintercept = 0, colour = "white", size = 3) + geom_line() + ggtitle("Remaining pattern")
how to easily fit that model to every country?
## 25.2.1 Nested data
extract out common code with a function and repeat using map function from purrr - to repeat an action for each country (a subset of rows), need a nested data frame
```r by_country <- gapminder %>% group_by(country, continent) %>% nest()
by_country ```

## 25.2.2 List-columns
now that have nested data frame, in good position to fit some models
```r country_model <- function(df) { lm(lifeExp ~ year, data = df) }
# and want to apply it to every data frame. apply country_model to each element models <- map(by_country$data, country_model) ```
better to store list of models as column in by_country data frame - storing related objects in columns key value of data frames - instead of creating new object in global env, create new variable in by_country - a job for mutate()!
r by_country <- by_country %>% mutate(model = map(data, country_model)) by_country

To create the last plot (showing the data for the countries with the worst model fits), we needed two steps: we created a data frame with one row per country and then semi-joined it to the original dataset. Its possible to avoid this join if we use unnest() instead of unnest(.drop = TRUE). How? from answers
r gapminder %>% group_by(country, continent) %>% nest() %>% mutate(model = map(data, ~lm(lifeExp ~ year, .))) %>% mutate(glance = map(model, broom::glance)) %>% unnest(glance) %>% unnest(data) %>% filter(r.squared < 0.25) %>% ggplot(aes(year, lifeExp)) + geom_line(aes(color = country))

25.3 List-columns

dive back into some of the details for managing many models, after seeing workflow

# base R doesn't make it easy to create list-columns
data.frame(x = list(1:3, 3:5))
##   x.1.3 x.3.5
## 1     1     3
## 2     2     4
## 3     3     5
# can prevent data.frame from doing this with I(), but result doesn't print well
data.frame(
  x = I(list(1:3, 3:5)), 
  y = c("1, 2", "3, 4, 5")
)
##         x       y
## 1 1, 2, 3    1, 2
## 2 3, 4, 5 3, 4, 5

tibble() is better

tibble(
  x = list(1:3, 3:5), 
  y = c("1, 2", "3, 4, 5")
)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   x         y      
##   <list>    <chr>  
## 1 <int [3]> 1, 2   
## 2 <int [3]> 3, 4, 5
# also easier with tribble(), automatically knows that need a list:
tribble(
   ~x, ~y,
  1:3, "1, 2",
  3:5, "3, 4, 5"
)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   x         y      
##   <list>    <chr>  
## 1 <int [3]> 1, 2   
## 2 <int [3]> 3, 4, 5

effective list-column pipeline: - create list-column using one of nest(), summarise() + list(), or mutate() + a map function - create other intermediate list-columns by transforming existing list columns with map(), map2(), or pmap() - simplify list-column back down to data frame or atomic vector

# 25.4 Creating list-columns
#25.5 Simplifying list-columns
to apply techniques of data manipulation and visualization learned in this book, need to simplify list-column back to regular column or set of columns - technique use to collapse down to simpler structure depends on whether want single value per element, or multiple values - if want single value, use mutate(), with map_lgl(), map_int(), map_dbl() and map_chr() to create atomic vector - if want many values, use unnest() to convert list-columns back to regular columns, repeating rows as many times as necessary
## 25.5.1 List to vector
if can reduce list column to atomic vector then will be regular column - ex can always summarise object with type and length, this code will work regardless of what sort of list-column you have
```r df <- tribble( ~x, letters[1:5], 1:3, runif(5) )
df %>% mutate( type = map_chr(x, typeof), length = map_int(x, length) ) ```
## # A tibble: 3 x 3 ## x type length ## <list> <chr> <int> ## 1 <chr [5]> character 5 ## 2 <int [3]> integer 3 ## 3 <dbl [5]> double 5
```r # also dont forget about map_*() shortcuts df <- tribble( ~x, list(a = 1, b = 2), list(a = 2, c = 4) )
df %>% mutate( a = map_dbl(x, a), b = map_dbl(x, b, .null = NA_real_) ) ```
## # A tibble: 2 x 3 ## x a b ## <list> <dbl> <dbl> ## 1 <named list [2]> 1 2 ## 2 <named list [2]> 2 NA
## 25.5.2 Unnesting
unnest() works by repeating regular columns once for each element of list-column
r tibble(x = 1:2, y = list(1:4, 1)) %>% unnest(y)
## # A tibble: 5 x 2 ## x y ## <int> <dbl> ## 1 1 1 ## 2 1 2 ## 3 1 3 ## 4 1 4 ## 5 2 1
```r # means cant simultaneously unnest two columns that contain different # of elements
# Ok, because y and z have the same number of elements in # every row df1 <- tribble( ~x, ~y, ~z, 1, c(a, b), 1:2, 2, c, 3 ) df1 ```
## # A tibble: 2 x 3 ## x y z ## <dbl> <list> <list> ## 1 1 <chr [2]> <int [2]> ## 2 2 <chr [1]> <dbl [1]>
r df1 %>% unnest(c(y, z))
## # A tibble: 3 x 3 ## x y z ## <dbl> <chr> <dbl> ## 1 1 a 1 ## 2 1 b 2 ## 3 2 c 3
r # Doesn't work because y and z have different number of elements df2 <- tribble( ~x, ~y, ~z, 1, "a", 1:2, 2, c("b", "c"), 3 ) df2
## # A tibble: 2 x 3 ## x y z ## <dbl> <list> <list> ## 1 1 <chr [1]> <int [2]> ## 2 2 <chr [2]> <dbl [1]>
r df2 %>% unnest(c(y, z))
## # A tibble: 4 x 3 ## x y z ## <dbl> <chr> <dbl> ## 1 1 a 1 ## 2 1 a 2 ## 3 2 b 3 ## 4 2 c 3
same principle applies when unnesting list-columns or data frames - can unnest multiple list-cols as long as all data frames in each row have same number of rows
## 25.5.3 Exercises
1. Why might the lengths() function be useful for creating atomic vector columns from list-columns? important to know if all elements have same length for list-columns!
2. List the most common types of vector found in a data frame. What makes lists different? logical, numeric, integer, character, factor all of common types of vectors in data frames are atomic. lsits are not atomic

25.6 Making tidy data with broom

broom package provides three general tools for turning models into tidy data frames - glance(model) - returns a row for each model. each column gives a model summary, either a measure of model quality, or complexity, or both - tidy(model) - returns row for each coefficient in the model. each column gives information about estimate or variability - augment(model, data) - returns a row for each row in data, adding extra values like residuals, influence statistics
